# Day 09 - Merge Sorted Array

## Problem Statement
You are given two integer arrays `nums1` and `nums2`, sorted in non-decreasing order, and two integers `m` and `n`, representing the number of valid elements in each array.

Merge `nums2` into `nums1` such that `nums1` becomes a single sorted array in non-decreasing order. The merged array should be stored directly in `nums1`, which has enough extra space to hold all the elements.

## Code

class Solution {
public:
    void merge(vector<int>& arr1, int m, vector<int>& arr2, int n) {
        int i = m - 1, j = n - 1, idx = m + n - 1;

        while (i >= 0 && j >= 0) {
            if (arr1[i] >= arr2[j]) {
                arr1[idx] = arr1[i];
                idx--;
                i--;
            } else {
                arr1[idx] = arr2[j];
                idx--;
                j--;
            }
        }

        while (j >= 0) {
            arr1[idx] = arr2[j];
            j--;
            idx--;
        }
    }
};




## Time Complexity
**O(m + n)**

## Space Complexity
**O(1)**

## Approach
This solution uses the **Two Pointer** technique by starting from the end of both arrays. Three pointers are maintained: one at the last valid element of `nums1`, one at the last element of `nums2`, and one at the last position of `nums1` where the next largest element should be placed. At each step, the larger of the two elements is placed at the current position, and the corresponding pointer is moved backward. After one array is exhausted, any remaining elements from `nums2` are copied into `nums1`. Since the merge is performed from the end, no existing elements in `nums1` are overwritten before being processed.
